Tips for identifying lip filler migration! One of the worst things we can do as injectors is filling on top of migrated filler. ⁣
⁣
The more we understand about anatomy, planes of the tissue, rheology, the better we understand how easily filler can migrate. ⁣
⁣
What I have learned over time is trying to impress a patient when there is visible migration NEVER works! Have the tough conversation of dissolving and stand firm. Let them know you care about their results for the long run. Show them examples of how dissolving and refilling will yield the best long term result. ⁣
⁣
I even tell my patients with tricky anatomy that despite us going slow and picking the right product, with all the movement in the lips there is still a chance for migration and what’s important is that they trust me if I recommend to do a little “clean up” dissolving every couple years. The more we learn about duration of fillers, the more of a reality this becomes. ⁣
⁣

The art of facial balancing by @nursemindyc ⁣
⁣
As a nurse injector I am looking at your unique anatomy, proportions, highlights, contours, deficits, ethnicity and more. All of this goes on inside of an injectors mind. ⁣
⁣
As we are aging we may go through periods of change in weight and can begin losing the good fat in our face and even bony structure.⁣
⁣
This patient of mine wanted natural and subtle enhancements only. ⁣
⁣
What she really needed was a little support to the midface since for us asians we tend to have more of a negative vector on our side profile. ⁣
⁣
In order to create more proportion and balance for her⁣
I used a fat mimicking filler to the midface as well as a bone mimicking filler to her chin to balance the asymmetries in the lower face. I also used a neuromodulator to control her gummy smile and she is loving her overall results. ⁣
⁣
Please remember that I want you looking and feeling like your best self. You are beautiful. You are wonderful and you deserve it all and more ❤️⁣
⁣
Thank you to this gorgeous woman for trusting me. She is beauty goals!⁣
⁣
Mindy, Nurse Injector 🪄 at @aere_aesthetics

Some of my favorite midface injection tips! Map this area and be strategic! Plumping this area up with volume is the worst approach to this area and will lead to looking overfilled. 

@professorsebastiancotofana identified the transverse facial septum in one of his papers and how this septum contributes to midface projection upon smiling. This further supports placing minimal product in the midface to avoid looking overfilled when smiling. 

I place enough product only to create support and highlight. The rest of my product goes to softening transition zones and balancing other features of the face such as chin and lower face. 

Always consider temples, lid-cheek junction, undereye shadows, submalar hollows and match structural support with the chin, chin shadows and lips for a highlight. 

Skillfull injections can create more contour and definition and although adding filler, when strategically placed, will create a less full and more sculpted result.

Injection Tips for treating the full face for the most natural result!
⁣
1. Treat every transition zone for the most impact ⁣
— temples, lid-cheek junction, preauricular area, chin shadows and prejowl sulcus are all almost always treated!⁣
⁣
2. Avoid what doesn’t need more volume⁣
— the cookie cutter method of always starting in the midface is over. I use only what’s necessary here and once it’s enough I save the remaining product for all the other areas that need to be addressed⁣
⁣
3. Look at the face 3 dimensionally
— from an oblique view you’re best able to shadows and bony recession imo. Start from the top and laterally and move down and across the face.

⁣
For this beautiful patient we treated the full face: 
• Temples⁣
• Midface⁣
• Lid-cheek junction ⁣
• Chin⁣
• Chin shadows⁣
• Jawline⁣
• Lips⁣
• Upper face Botox⁣
• Lower face Botox⁣
⁣
*4 Syringes used ⁣

She has a more restored appearance now yet still looks natural and like herself. Can I use more filler? Yes. Is it necessary? No.⁣

We discussed combining with Sculptra or Threads at a future visit to protect her results by also stimulating collagen. ⁣

I will always recommend a more comprehensive and anti-aging approach. Using only fillers overtime can create heaviness and I prefer a more natural and lifted end result. ⁣

A few of my favorite pearls on ways to approach a full face rejuvenation. ⁣
⁣
My favorite way to approach the face is by looking at it 3-dimensionally.⁣
⁣
I start by treating top to bottom and then I look at:⁣
• facial proportions⁣
• light vs shadows⁣
• most striking features⁣
• convexities vs concavities.
• transition zones 
⁣
It’s important to focus on restoring structure and light to the lateral face for a balanced result from all angles! 

Too much filler in the central face  will herniate with smiling and animation and is more prone to causing an over-filled look.

I am absolutely obsessed with what Ultrasound is offering the industry, I believe it is revolutionary for understanding product migration patterns, treating complications and identifying nodules. However, do I think it needs to be used with every patient and that it will entirely prevent complications, not so much.

We now know the risk of arterial spasm with HA injections without filler even being injected intra-arterially. So vascular mapping can be helpful but will it 100% prevent an occlusion or a complication, no.

We know filler migrates, but if it isn’t causing problems, is it 100% worth starting the dissolve and refill cycle? Maybe my opinion will change in the future but for now if it’s not visible on the surface anatomy then I’m not sure if it’s worth chasing.

This is also why half of my practice consists of combining with collagen-stimulating treatments like PRFM and Threads to help improve the integrity of the tissue and prevent filler fatigue.

I’ve had filler in my face for over 10 years and I’m sure if I was fully scanned you’d see filler everywhere. But only if the filler looks distorted or visible will I go through dissolving. I maintain my tissue thickness and tightness with other modalities so my filler doesn’t look visible overtime, this is the key! 

Injectors, I challenge you to incorporate US in your practice as it is revolutionary for treating complications but remember it isn’t going to keep you 100% safe. We should still treat slowly and carefully with long-term outcomes in mind and combine with biorejuvenating treatments so the filler doesn’t look visible over time.

If you are interested in learning more on US or attending a training, I highly recommend @pa.Nicola and @facialultrasound course, I’ve also attended @sonosthetics. Some others I’ve heard wonderful things about and look forward to attending in the future are @thestellacenter and @dani_sparkle_pa.

Natural Rejuvination?? Yes Please!! That’s what we specialize in! PRF is one of our most popular treatments. 💉 😍

What is PRF? Platelet-Rich Fibrin treatments harness your body’s own healing magic by using your own platelets and turning into a gel matrix that is injected in the skin and boosts the collagen and elastin in the skin to refresh and revitalize your skin. 

Everyone can benefit from this treatment. Our most popular area is for the undereyes since this is a delicate area and we have to be very careful with filler. For anyone who wants to improve their Undereyes but don’t know or are nervous for filler, this is for you.

Our dear patient here is resistant to Botox and I’m so glad we can offer her an option that is safe and still rejuvenates the skin.

There is some downtime associated with it but it’s worth having a collagen boost and to improve one of the most difficult areas to treat but also one of the most important, the Undereyes.
